Backend — resume_ranker/backend/app.py

Create this file and paste:

python
# backend/app.py
import os
import logging
import traceback
from flask import Flask, request, jsonify
from flask_cors import CORS
from werkzeug.utils import secure_filename
from model import rank_resumes, extract_text  # local model functions

# Config
UPLOAD_FOLDER = "resumes"
os.makedirs(UPLOAD_FOLDER, exist_ok=True)
MAX_MB = 25
ALLOWED_EXT = {".pdf", ".txt"}

# App setup
app = Flask(__name__)
app.config["UPLOAD_FOLDER"] = UPLOAD_FOLDER
app.config["MAX_CONTENT_LENGTH"] = MAX_MB * 1024 * 1024
CORS(app)

# Logging
logging.basicConfig(level=logging.INFO,
                    format="%(asctime)s %(levelname)s: %(message)s",
                    handlers=[logging.StreamHandler(), logging.FileHandler("server.log", encoding='utf-8')])
logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)

@app.errorhandler(Exception)
def handle_exception(e):
    logger.exception("Unhandled exception")
    return jsonify({"error": str(e), "trace": traceback.format_exc()}), 500

@app.route("/health", methods=["GET"])
def health():
    return jsonify({"status": "ok"})

@app.route("/rank", methods=["POST"])
def rank():
    files = request.files.getlist("files")
    if not files:
        return jsonify({"error": "No files provided"}), 400

    saved_files = []
    for f in files:
        filename = secure_filename(f.filename)
        ext = os.path.splitext(filename)[1].lower()
        if ext not in ALLOWED_EXT:
            logger.warning("Rejected file due to extension: %s", filename)
            continue
        save_path = os.path.join(app.config["UPLOAD_FOLDER"], filename)
        f.save(save_path)
        logger.info("Saved file: %s (%d bytes)", save_path, os.path.getsize(save_path))
        # optional small sanity read
        txt = extract_text(save_path)
        if not txt.strip():
            logger.warning("No extractable text from: %s", save_path)
        saved_files.append(save_path)

    results = rank_resumes(app.config["UPLOAD_FOLDER"])
    logger.info("Rank results: %s", results)
    return jsonify(results)

Backend — resume_ranker/backend/model.py

Create this file and paste:

python
# backend/model.py
import os
import re
from typing import List, Dict
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity
import PyPDF2

JOB_DESC = """
We are hiring a Python Developer skilled in Flask, Machine Learning,
and REST APIs. Experience with SQL and cloud is a plus.
"""

def extract_text(file_path: str) -> str:
    ext = os.path.splitext(file_path)[1].lower()
    if ext == ".txt":
        with open(file_path, "r", encoding="utf-8", errors="ignore") as f:
            return f.read()
    text = ""
    try:
        with open(file_path, "rb") as f:
            reader = PyPDF2.PdfReader(f)
            for page in reader.pages:
                page_text = page.extract_text()
                if page_text:
                    text += page_text + "\n"
    except Exception:
        # return empty string on failure; caller can log/handle
        return ""
    return text

def rank_resumes(folder: str = "resumes") -> List[Dict]:
    # build TF-IDF on job description (fits the small example)
    vec = TfidfVectorizer(stop_words="english")
    jd_vec = vec.fit_transform([JOB_DESC])
    results = []
    for fname in os.listdir(folder):
        if not fname.lower().endswith((".pdf", ".txt")):
            continue
        path = os.path.join(folder, fname)
        text = extract_text(path)
        if not text:
            results.append({"name": fname, "score": 0.0, "note": "no text"})
            continue
        try:
            rv = vec.transform([text])
            score = float(cosine_similarity(jd_vec, rv)[0,0])
            results.append({"name": fname, "score": round(score*100, 2)})
        except ValueError:
            # empty vocab or transform error
            results.append({"name": fname, "score": 0.0, "note": "transform failed"})
    results.sort(key=lambda x: x.get("score", 0), reverse=True)
    return results

resume_ranker/frontend/src/App.jsx

jsx
// frontend/src/App.jsx
import React, { useState } from "react";
import axios from "axios";
import UploadBox from "./components/UploadBox";
import ResultsTable from "./components/ResultsTable";
import ScoreChart from "./components/ScoreChart";
import "./index.css";

export default function App() {
  const [results, setResults] = useState([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);

  async function handleUpload(files) {
    const fd = new FormData();
    for (let f of files) fd.append("files", f);
    setLoading(true);
    try {
      const res = await axios.post("http://127.0.0.1:5000/rank", fd, {
        headers: { "Content-Type": "multipart/form-data" }
      });
      setResults(res.data);
    } catch (e) {
      alert("Upload failed: " + (e.response?.data?.error || e.message));
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  }

  return (
    <div className="container">
      <h1>AI Resume Ranker</h1>
      <div className="card">
        <UploadBox onUpload={handleUpload} />
        {loading && <p>Processing...</p>}
        {results.length > 0 && (
          <>
            <ResultsTable data={results} />
            <ScoreChart data={results} />
          </>
        )}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

resume_ranker/frontend/src/components/UploadBox.jsx

jsx
// frontend/src/components/UploadBox.jsx
import React from "react";

export default function UploadBox({ onUpload }) {
  const handleChange = (e) => {
    if (e.target.files.length === 0) return;
    onUpload(e.target.files);
  };
  return (
    <div style={{ marginBottom: 12 }}>
      <input type="file" multiple onChange={handleChange} />
      <p style={{ color: "#9ca3af" }}>Upload PDFs or TXT resumes</p>
    </div>
  );
}

resume_ranker/frontend/src/components/ResultsTable.jsx

jsx
// frontend/src/components/ResultsTable.jsx
import React from "react";

export default function ResultsTable({ data }) {
  return (
    <table style={{ width: "100%", marginTop: 12, borderCollapse: "collapse" }}>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style={{ textAlign: "left" }}>Resume</th>
          <th style={{ textAlign: "left" }}>Score (%)</th>
          <th style={{ textAlign: "left" }}>Note</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {data.map((r, i) => (
          <tr key={i} style={{ borderTop: "1px solid #111827" }}>
            <td>{r.name}</td>
            <td>{r.score}</td>
            <td>{r.note || ""}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  );
}

resume_ranker/frontend/src/components/ScoreChart.jsx

jsx
// frontend/src/components/ScoreChart.jsx
import React from "react";
import { BarChart, Bar, XAxis, YAxis, Tooltip, ResponsiveContainer } from "recharts";

export default function ScoreChart({ data }) {
  const chartData = data.map((d) => ({ name: d.name, score: d.score }));
  return (
    <div style={{ width: "100%", height: 240, marginTop: 18 }}>
      <ResponsiveContainer>
        <BarChart data={chartData}>
          <XAxis dataKey="name" stroke="#9ca3af" />
          <YAxis stroke="#9ca3af" />
          <Tooltip />
          <Bar dataKey="score" fill="#6366f1" />
        </BarChart>
      </ResponsiveContainer>
    </div>
  );
}

Step-by-step Debugging (exact places to run and what to check)

Below is an ordered troubleshooting checklist. For each step I tell you where (which file or terminal) to act.

0 — Before you start: run health checks

Where: Backend terminal (resume_ranker/backend)
Commands:

bash
# in backend
. .venv/Scripts/activate         # Windows, or source .venv/bin/activate
python app.py

Expected: Flask server starts on http://127.0.0.1:5000. Open http://127.0.0.1:5000/health in browser — should return {"status":"ok"}.

If it fails:

  • Check backend/server.log (created by logger) for stack trace.

  • Error message says missing package → pip install missing ones.

1 — ModuleNotFoundError or import problems

Where: Backend terminal / file: backend/requirements.txt
Fix:

bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
# or install a specific package, e.g.
pip install PyPDF2 flask flask-cors scikit-learn

Also ensure you run with the Python inside backend/.venv (activate it).

2 — Test backend without frontend (isolate)

Where: Terminal (backend folder)
Action: Use curl to POST files directly to endpoint.

bash
curl -v -F "files=@test_resumes/alice.pdf" -F "files=@test_resumes/bob.pdf" http://127.0.0.1:5000/rank

What to expect:

  • JSON array of {name, score,...} returned.

  • If response 413 → large file, change MAX_CONTENT_LENGTH in app.py.

  • If response 400 with "No files provided" → check that curl used correct -F key name files.

3 — If PDFs return note: no text or scores 0

Where: Edit backend/model.py and backend/app.py logging lines.

  • Open backend/model.py and add debug print near extraction:

python
text = extract_text(path)
print("DEBUG: text len for", fname, len(text))

  • If length is 0:

    • The PDF may be a scanned image. PyPDF2 cannot OCR scanned images.

    • Fix: use OCR — add pytesseract + pdf2image. Example (where to add): replace extract_text in model.py with OCR fallback:

python
# install: pip install pytesseract pdf2image pillow
from pdf2image import convert_from_path
import pytesseract

def extract_text(...):
    # try PyPDF2 first...
    if not text.strip():
        pages = convert_from_path(file_path, dpi=200)
        for pg in pages:
            text += pytesseract.image_to_string(pg)

  • Note: OCR requires system Tesseract installed separately.

4 — Frontend → Backend connectivity problems (CORS / URL / Network)

Where: Frontend console (browser DevTools → Console & Network tabs) and frontend/src/App.jsx.

Symptoms and fixes:

  • Network Error or status 0 → Backend not running or wrong URL. In App.jsx ensure URL: http://127.0.0.1:5000/rank.

  • CORS error in console → Backend needs CORS: from flask_cors import CORS; CORS(app) (this is already in app.py).

  • 403 / 404 → Wrong endpoint path or method (use POST to /rank).

Test: In browser open DevTools → Network → perform upload → click the failed request → inspect Request URL, Request Headers, Response.

5 — React errors / app won't start

Where: Frontend terminal

  • Run:

bash
cd resume_ranker/frontend
npm start

  • If npm errors: delete node_modules + package-lock.json then npm install.

  • If app runs but blank page: open Browser DevTools Console and fix errors shown (import issues, missing components, etc).

6 — Unexpected empty TF-IDF vocabulary or transform errors

Where: backend/model.py and logs (server.log)

  • Symptom: "transform failed" or ValueError: empty vocabulary.

  • Cause: JOB_DESC empty or vectorizer got only empty docs (e.g., all resumes had no text).

  • Fix: ensure JOB_DESC non-empty and there are at least some non-empty resume texts. Add guard in rank_resumes:

python
if not any(texts): return [{"name":"none","score":0,"note":"no text in any file"}]

7 — Large file / performance concerns

Where: backend/app.py adjust MAX_CONTENT_LENGTH and model.extract_text to read only first N pages.

  • In model.py modify to only read first 5 pages:

python
for page in reader.pages[:5]:
    text += (page.extract_text() or "")

8 — Debugging step-by-step with example scenario

Scenario A: Upload returns empty result list on UI

  1. Check frontend network log (Browser devtools → Network): did the POST request send files?

    • If no: fix UploadBox.jsx event handling.

  2. Check backend logs (backend/server.log): did the /rank call arrive? any exceptions logged?

  3. Curl test: replicate POST from terminal to verify backend independent of frontend.

  4. Check resumes/ folder: are files saved? if not, permission issue or wrong secure_filename.

  5. Open one uploaded PDF manually: can you copy text? If not — scanned PDF (need OCR).

Scenario B: API returns scores but UI shows nothing

  1. Inspect axios response in frontend console (console.log(res.data) in App.jsx).

  2. Ensure ResultsTable expects keys name, score; adapt if response structure different.

  3. Confirm React state setResults is called and not overwritten.

9 — Logging & persistent debug artifacts

  • Where to look: resume_ranker/backend/server.log (configured in app.py)

  • Add extra debug prints in model.py and app.py near suspected lines.

  • Example:

python
logger.debug("Text snippet: %s", text[:200])

10 — Tests you can run / quick checks (commands)

  • Start backend:

bash
cd resume_ranker/backend
. .venv/Scripts/activate
python app.py

  • Test health:

bash
curl http://127.0.0.1:5000/health
# expected {"status":"ok"}

  • Test ranking (replace with real PDF path):

bash
curl -F "files=@/path/to/resume1.pdf" -F "files=@/path/to/resume2.pdf" http://127.0.0.1:5000/rank

  • From frontend folder:

bash
cd resume_ranker/frontend
npm start
# open http://localhost:3000 and upload files

11 — Final notes & next steps

  • If you want explainability (why a resume scored X): expand backend model.py to compute top TF-IDF terms and numeric feature contribution. (I included an earlier explain example in previous message — I can integrate.)

  • For production: consider saving TF-IDF vectorizer persistent and only transforming new resumes (faster), or using a job queue (Celery) for heavy PDF/OCR tasks.

  • If you want me to add OCR fallback code, or provide a Dockerfile to containerize the backend, tell me and I’ll add it.

  • provide a small unit-test file to automatically validate rank_resumes.

2) Supabase — DB schema (SQL)

Run this SQL in Supabase SQL editor. It creates resumes, profiles, and rankings. Supabase stores user auth in auth.users (we reference auth.users in profiles). See Supabase docs for referencing auth.users. Supabase+1

sql
-- 1) user profiles (link to supabase auth)
create table if not exists public.profiles (
  id uuid primary key references auth.users(id) on delete cascade,
  full_name text,
  email text,
  created_at timestamptz default now()
);

-- 2) resumes table (metadata + storage path)
create table if not exists public.resumes (
  id uuid primary key default gen_random_uuid(),
  user_id uuid references public.profiles(id),
  filename text not null,
  storage_path text not null, -- e.g. "resumes/<uuid>.pdf" in Supabase Storage
  uploaded_at timestamptz default now(),
  text_content text, -- extracted text
  is_ocr boolean default false
);

-- 3) embeddings stored as vector (we'll use float8[] for simplicity)
create table if not exists public.resume_embeddings (
  id uuid primary key default gen_random_uuid(),
  resume_id uuid references public.resumes(id) on delete cascade,
  embedding float8[] not null,
  created_at timestamptz default now()
);

-- 4) ranking results for a given job/request
create table if not exists public.rankings (
  id uuid primary key default gen_random_uuid(),
  job_title text,
  job_description text,
  created_by uuid references public.profiles(id),
  created_at timestamptz default now()
);

create table if not exists public.ranking_items (
  id uuid primary key default gen_random_uuid(),
  ranking_id uuid references public.rankings(id) on delete cascade,
  resume_id uuid references public.resumes(id),
  score numeric, -- percentage or similarity score
  note text
);

backend/app/embeddings.py

(creates embeddings via OpenAI; wrap into function)

python
# app/embeddings.py
import os
import openai
from typing import List
openai.api_key = os.getenv("OPENAI_API_KEY")

EMBED_MODEL = os.getenv("OPENAI_EMBED_MODEL", "text-embedding-3-large")  # recommended
# Create embedding vector for a list of texts
def get_embeddings(texts: List[str]) -> List[List[float]]:
    # OpenAI Python client: create embeddings
    resp = openai.Embedding.create(model=EMBED_MODEL, input=texts)
    # resp['data'] is a list, keep resp['data'][i]['embedding']
    return [d["embedding"] for d in resp["data"]]

(Citation for model: OpenAI docs on text-embedding-3-large). OpenAI Platform

backend/app/models.py

(helpers: PDF text extraction + OCR fallback)

python
# app/models.py
import fitz  # PyMuPDF
import pytesseract
from PIL import Image
import io

def extract_text_from_pdf(path: str, ocr_if_empty: bool = True) -> (str, bool):
    """
    Returns (text, used_ocr_flag)
    """
    text = ""
    doc = fitz.open(path)
    for page in doc:
        txt = page.get_text()
        if txt:
            text += txt + "\n"
    used_ocr = False
    if ocr_if_empty and not text.strip():
        # render pages to images and OCR
        used_ocr = True
        for i in range(len(doc)):
            pix = doc[i].get_pixmap(dpi=200)
            img = Image.open(io.BytesIO(pix.tobytes()))
            page_text = pytesseract.image_to_string(img)
            if page_text:
                text += page_text + "\n"
    return text, used_ocr

backend/app/send_email.py

(SendGrid flow for shortlisting)

python
# app/send_email.py
import os
from sendgrid import SendGridAPIClient
from sendgrid.helpers.mail import Mail

SENDGRID_API_KEY = os.getenv("SENDGRID_API_KEY")
FROM_EMAIL = os.getenv("FROM_EMAIL")  # e.g. "hr@company.com"

def send_shortlist_email(to_email: str, candidate_name: str, job_title: str, message: str):
    sg = SendGridAPIClient(SENDGRID_API_KEY)
    subject = f"You've been shortlisted for {job_title}"
    content = f"Hi {candidate_name},\n\n{message}\n\nRegards,\nHiring Team"
    mail = Mail(from_email=FROM_EMAIL, to_emails=to_email, subject=subject, plain_text_content=content)
    resp = sg.send(mail)
    return resp.status_code, resp.body, resp.headers

backend/app/main.py

(Main FastAPI – endpoints: health, upload resume, index embeddings, rank, shortlist)

This is a compact version — adapt DB insert/update code to your Supabase client usage.

python
# app/main.py
import os
import io
from fastapi import FastAPI, UploadFile, File, Form, HTTPException
from fastapi.middleware.cors import CORSMiddleware
from typing import List
from .models import extract_text_from_pdf
from .embeddings import get_embeddings
from .send_email import send_shortlist_email
from supabase import create_client
import numpy as np
import uuid
from pydantic import BaseModel

# Supabase client
SUPABASE_URL = os.getenv("SUPABASE_URL")
SUPABASE_KEY = os.getenv("SUPABASE_KEY")
supabase = create_client(SUPABASE_URL, SUPABASE_KEY)

app = FastAPI(title="Resume Ranker")

app.add_middleware(
    CORSMiddleware,
    allow_origins=["*"],  # restrict in prod
    allow_methods=["*"],
    allow_headers=["*"],
)

@app.get("/health")
def health():
    return {"status": "ok"}

class RankRequest(BaseModel):
    job_title: str
    job_description: str
    created_by: str = None  # optional supabase profile id uuid

@app.post("/upload")
async def upload_resume(user_id: str = Form(...), file: UploadFile = File(...)):
    # save to Supabase Storage
    content = await file.read()
    fname = f"resumes/{uuid.uuid4()}_{file.filename}"
    # upload to supabase storage (bucket 'resumes' must exist)
    res = supabase.storage.from_('resumes').upload(fname, io.BytesIO(content), content_type=file.content_type)
    if res.get('error'):
        raise HTTPException(status_code=500, detail=res['error'])
    # extract text (requires saving locally)
    local_path = f"/tmp/{uuid.uuid4()}_{file.filename}"
    with open(local_path, "wb") as f:
        f.write(content)
    text, used_ocr = extract_text_from_pdf(local_path)
    # insert resume metadata
    r = supabase.table('resumes').insert({
        "user_id": user_id,
        "filename": file.filename,
        "storage_path": fname,
        "text_content": text,
        "is_ocr": used_ocr
    }).execute()
    return {"ok": True, "resume": r.data}

@app.post("/index-embeddings")
def index_embeddings(resume_ids: List[str]):
    # fetch resumes by ids, compute embeddings and store
    rows = supabase.table('resumes').select('id, text_content').in_('id', resume_ids).execute()
    items = rows.data
    texts = [it['text_content'] or "" for it in items]
    embeddings = get_embeddings(texts)
    # insert into resume_embeddings
    for i, it in enumerate(items):
        supabase.table('resume_embeddings').insert({
            "resume_id": it['id'],
            "embedding": embeddings[i]
        }).execute()
    return {"indexed": len(items)}

@app.post("/rank")
def rank(req: RankRequest):
    # 1) create ranking record
    r = supabase.table('rankings').insert({
        "job_title": req.job_title,
        "job_description": req.job_description,
        "created_by": req.created_by
    }).execute()
    ranking_id = r.data[0]['id']
    # 2) compute embedding for job description
    q_vec = get_embeddings([req.job_description])[0]
    # 3) fetch resume embeddings from DB
    rows = supabase.table('resume_embeddings').select('resume_id, embedding').execute()
    items = rows.data
    results = []
    for it in items:
        emb = np.array(it['embedding'], dtype=float)
        q = np.array(q_vec, dtype=float)
        # cosine similarity
        sim = float(np.dot(q, emb) / (np.linalg.norm(q) * np.linalg.norm(emb) + 1e-10))
        results.append((it['resume_id'], sim))
    # sort desc
    results.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
    # store ranking_items and return top results with resume metadata
    out = []
    for resume_id, score in results:
        supabase.table('ranking_items').insert({
            "ranking_id": ranking_id,
            "resume_id": resume_id,
            "score": float(score)
        }).execute()
        # fetch resume metadata
        meta = supabase.table('resumes').select('id, filename, storage_path').eq('id', resume_id).single().execute().data
        out.append({"resume": meta, "score": float(score)})
    return {"ranking_id": ranking_id, "results": out}

@app.post("/shortlist")
def shortlist(ranking_id: str, resume_id: str, note: str = ""):
    # fetch resume metadata to get uploader / email
    resume = supabase.table('resumes').select('id, user_id, filename, text_content').eq('id', resume_id).single().execute().data
    # fetch profile to get email
    profile = supabase.table('profiles').select('email, full_name').eq('id', resume['user_id']).single().execute().data
    # send email
    job = supabase.table('rankings').select('job_title').eq('id', ranking_id).single().execute().data
    subject = job['job_title'] if job else "Shortlisted"
    message = f"You have been shortlisted for {subject}. Note: {note}"
    status, body, headers = send_shortlist_email(profile['email'], profile['full_name'], subject, message)
    return {"status": status}

Security tip: In production, do not allow allow_origins=["*"] — restrict to your frontend domain.

frontend/src/pages/index.tsx

tsx
// src/pages/index.tsx
import React, { useState } from "react";
import axios from "axios";

export default function Home() {
  const [files, setFiles] = useState<FileList | null>(null);
  const [results, setResults] = useState<any[]>([]);

  async function handleUpload() {
    if (!files) return alert("Choose files");
    const fd = new FormData();
    // use a sample user/profile id from supabase for demo or let user sign in
    const userId = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_DEMO_USER_ID || "";
    for (let i = 0; i < files.length; i++) fd.append("file", files[i]);
    fd.append("user_id", userId);
    const resp = await axios.post(`${process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE}/upload`, fd, {
      headers: {'Content-Type': 'multipart/form-data'}
    });
    alert("Uploaded");
  }

  async function handleRank() {
    const job = prompt("Enter job description / job title") || "";
    const resp = await axios.post(`${process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE}/rank`, {
      job_title: "Hiring - " + job.slice(0, 30),
      job_description: job,
      created_by: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_DEMO_USER_ID || null
    });
    setResults(resp.data.results || []);
  }

  return (
    <div style={{ padding: 24 }}>
      <h1>AI Resume Ranker</h1>
      <input type="file" multiple onChange={(e) => setFiles(e.target.files)} />
      <button onClick={handleUpload}>Upload</button>
      <button onClick={handleRank}>Rank</button>

      <div style={{ marginTop: 20 }}>
        {results.map((r: any) => (
          <div key={r.resume.id} style={{ borderBottom: "1px solid #ddd", padding: 8 }}>
            <strong>{r.resume.filename}</strong> — score: {(r.score*100).toFixed(2)}%
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

8) SendGrid shortlisting flow (detailed)

  1. Shortlist in UI: recruiter clicks "shortlist" next to a candidate → frontend calls POST /shortlist with ranking_id and resume_id.

  2. Backend /shortlist:

    • Looks up resume metadata and profile email from Supabase.

    • Builds a short email message with job_title and optional note.

    • Calls SendGrid via sendgrid Python SDK to send the email (we used send_shortlist_email).

  3. Track status: Save SendGrid response or store a shortlist_history table if you want persistence.

10) Extra production notes & recommendations

  • Vector DB: For large-scale, move embeddings out of Postgres into a proper vector DB (Pinecone, Milvus, or Supabase Vector if available). Many tutorials show FastAPI + Pinecone patterns. Python in Plain EnglishPinecone

  • Security: Use fine-grained RLS policies in Supabase to protect resume data. Do not expose keys to the frontend.

  • Batching: Batch embeddings calls for many resumes to reduce API costs.

  • OCR: Tesseract must be installed on Docker image (apt-get update && apt-get install -y tesseract-ocr libtesseract-dev) if you need OCR fallback.

  • Costs: OpenAI embeddings & SendGrid costs apply — monitor usage.

  |    |
  |    \- /rank -> queries [Vector DB] & [Postgres] for metadata

[Supabase Postgres] (profiles, metadata, rankings)

Components & responsibilities

  • Next.js (Frontend)

    • UI, upload widget, ranking dashboard, sign-in (Supabase Auth), server-side rendering for SEO.

    • Environment: TypeScript, Tailwind, Recharts.

  • FastAPI (Backend)

    • Handles uploads, text extraction orchestration, embedding requests, ranking, shortlisting emails, admin APIs, health & metrics.

    • Endpoints described later.

  • Supabase Storage

    • Store original resume files (private bucket), thumbnails, extracted text blobs (optional).

  • Supabase Postgres

    • Relational metadata: profiles, resumes table, rankings, audit logs.

  • Vector DB (Pinecone / Milvus / Supabase Vector)

    • High-performance similarity search on embeddings for ranking.

  • Embedding Service

    • OpenAI / local SBERT microservice. Can be a separate service or called from FastAPI.

  • SendGrid

    • Shortlist email service (transactions + templates).

  • Monitoring & Logs

    • Prometheus + Grafana (K8s) or 3rd-party (Datadog / Sentry) for errors, latency, usage and model drift.

Key API endpoints (web-facing)

  • POST /upload — Upload file, return resume_id (saves to Supabase Storage + metadata)

  • POST /index-embeddings — (async) compute & store embeddings for resume IDs

  • POST /rank — Input: {job_title, job_description, top_k} → returns ordered list of resumes (metadata + score)

  • GET /rank/{ranking_id} — Get stored ranking results

  • POST /shortlist — {ranking_id, resume_id, note} → triggers SendGrid email

  • GET /health — service health

  • GET /metrics — Prometheus metrics

Dataflow (high level)

  1. User uploads resume via Next.js → POST /upload

  2. FastAPI saves file to Supabase Storage and metadata to Postgres. Creates resume_id.

  3. FastAPI triggers async /index-embeddings: extract text (PyMuPDF + OCR fallback), call Embedding Service (OpenAI or SBERT), write embedding into Vector DB and resume_embeddings table.

  4. Recruiter calls /rank with job description → FastAPI requests embedding for job description → queries Vector DB → retrieves top K resume IDs → fetches metadata from Postgres → returns ranked list.

  5. Recruiter shortlists candidate → /shortlist sends email via SendGrid and writes audit log into Postgres.

Deployment topology options

  • Small / staging: Docker Compose (backend + frontend local + supabase cloud)

  • Production (simple): Next.js -> Vercel; FastAPI -> Render (Docker) or Railway; Supabase hosted; Pinecone hosted; SendGrid.

  • Production (scale): Kubernetes (EKS/GKE) with autoscaling, ingress (NGINX), Redis for job queue, Horizontal Pod Autoscaler.

Scaling & reliability notes

  • Use async I/O in FastAPI for handling uploads & embedding calls.

  • Offload heavy compute (OCR, embedding) to worker queue (Celery/RQ + Redis) for throughput and retries.

  • Use vector DB for fast nearest-neighbor — Postgres + PGVector is OK for small scale; migrate when >100k items.

  • Cache frequent job descriptions embedding in Redis.

  • Use S3-compatible storage (Supabase or AWS S3) with server-side encryption.

Security

  • Use HTTPS everywhere, HSTS.

  • Do not expose SUPABASE_KEY or OPENAI_KEY to frontend.

  • Supabase: enable RLS policies so users can only see their resumes.

  • Use signed URLs for resume downloads (time-limited).

  • Validate uploaded file types and sizes; sandbox extractors; run virus scan if required.

  • Audit logs for shortlisting & access.

ML Architecture (Data pipeline, models, indexing, monitoring)

Summary

Pipeline: Resume files → Text extraction (+ OCR) → Normalization → Chunking → Embedding → Indexing (Vector DB) → Retrieval/Ranking → Explainability/Feedback → Monitoring & Retraining.

ASCII ML pipeline diagram

[Raw Resumes (PDF/DOCX/TXT)]
         |
         v
[Text Extractor]
  (PyMuPDF/pdfplumber -> text)
  fallback -> [OCR: Tesseract]
         |
         v
[Preprocessing]
  - clean, normalize, remove PII, split to chunks
  - language detection, encoding normalization
         |
         v
[Embeddings Generator]
  - OpenAI embeddings OR Local SBERT service
         |
         v
[Vector DB / Index]
  - Pinecone / Milvus / PGVector
         |
         v
[Similarity Search / Ranker] <--- [Job description -> embedding]
  - cosine similarity, re-ranking with features
         |
         v
[Explainability (term highlights / top tokens)]
         |
         v
[Dashboard + Recruiter UI]

Components & responsibilities

  • Text Extractor

    • PyMuPDF or pdfplumber for text PDFs. If empty (scanned), render to images and OCR with Tesseract. Save text_content to DB.

  • Preprocessor

    • Normalize whitespace, remove non-text noise, optionally anonymize PII, and chunk long docs (512–1024 tokens) with overlap for embedding.

  • Embedding Generator

    • Primary: OpenAI text-embedding-3-large (or similar) — high quality, easy. Alternative: local Sentence-BERT (all-MiniLM / all-mpnet) for cost control.

    • Batch embeddings (up to model limits) to reduce API calls/cost.

  • Vector DB / Index

    • Use Pinecone (managed, fast), Milvus (open-source), Supabase Vector or Postgres + pgvector for small scale.

    • Store metadata references (resume_id) alongside vectors.

  • Ranking & Re-ranking

    • Stage 1: vector similarity (cosine) to get candidate set.

    • Stage 2: optional logistic/regression model or a reranker (cross-encoder) to refine top N using full resume + JD context.

    • Combine features: semantic similarity, keyword overlap, recency, role match, years experience (structured).

  • Explainability

    • Return top contributing chunks/highlighted phrases (TF-IDF or attention/gradients) to explain scores to recruiter.

  • Monitoring & Drift Detection

    • Monitor distribution of embedding norms, top similarities, and recruiter feedback (shortlist conversions). Use these to flag drift and trigger retraining.

Detailed data flow for ranking request

  1. Recruiter submits JD.

  2. Backend preprocesses JD (normalize + chunk if long).

  3. Get JD embedding from Embedding Service.

  4. Query Vector DB for top-K nearest neighbors (IDs + distances).

  5. Fetch resume metadata and text chunks for these top-K from Postgres/Storage.

  6. Optional re-ranker: run cross-encoder (SBERT cross-encoder or transformer re-ranker) on JD + each candidate text chunk to get refined scores.

  7. Aggregate scores (e.g., weighted average of semantic sim + recency + keyword match).

  8. Return ranked results + explanation.

Feature engineering ideas for improved ranking

  • Keyword presence / frequency vs JD

  • Semantic similarity (embedding)

  • Role experience (parsed as structured feature)

  • Education match / certifications match

  • Recency of resume upload

  • Recruiter feedback / ground-truth (labels from past hires) for supervised retraining

Training & Retraining workflow

  • Store labeled events: candidate shortlisted, interview → convert to binary label (good/bad).

  • Periodically train a small supervised reranker (e.g., logistic regression over features, or fine-tune a LightGBM/ranker).

  • Validate on holdout set. Use AUC/precision@k for metrics.

  • CI for model deploy (canary rollout for reranker).

Latency & throughput targets

  • Real-time ranking: <500ms to return candidate IDs from vector DB for typical top-k. Re-ranking with cross-encoder may add 100–500ms per candidate; consider async or batch re-rank for UX.

  • Embedding generation: depends on model; external API latency (OpenAI) typically 100–400ms per batch. Use batching and background workers for large jobs.

Storage & retention

  • Keep raw resumes in storage for 1–3 years (configurable).

  • Keep extracted text and embeddings (smaller) long term for indexing and analytics.

  • Comply with privacy laws: provide delete-on-request flows and PII redaction.

Observability & metrics

  • Track: request latency, embedding call counts, vector DB queries per minute, conversion rates (shortlists → interviews), average similarity scores, error rates.

  • Use Sentry for errors, Prometheus/Grafana for metrics, ELK / Papertrail for logs.

Cost considerations (high level)

  • OpenAI embeddings: per-embedding cost → batch to optimize. If heavy usage -> consider local SBERT.

  • Vector DB: Pinecone charges by index + queries; PGVector cheaper at low scale.

  • Storage: Supabase/S3 minimal; large volumes increase cost.

  • SendGrid: charges per email beyond free tier.
